  "segments": [
    {
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 5.2,
      "text": "There's a pattern here that shows up across industries, not just cheaper materials,"
    },
    {
      "start": 6.0,
      "end": 8.42,
      "text": "a deeper shift in how things are made."
    },
    {
      "start": 10.16,
      "end": 15.16,
      "text": "Consider injection molding. Before it existed, you crafted individual objects."
    },
    {
      "start": 15.74,
      "end": 17.88,
      "text": "After it, you designed molds."
    },
    {
      "start": 19.58,
      "end": 23.24,
      "text": "Make the mold once, produce unlimited identical parts."
    },
    {
      "start": 23.9,
      "end": 27.82,
      "text": "Refine the mold once, every future part improves automatically."
    },
    {
      "start": 29.02,
      "end": 33.24,
      "text": "And when there's a defect, you don't patch individual parts."
    },
    {
      "start": 33.86,
      "end": 38.62,
      "text": "You fix the mold, and that fix applies to every part you'll ever make again."
    },
    {
      "start": 40.36,
      "end": 46.52,
      "text": "This is the real shift, not cheaper material, a migration of where value lives."
    },
    {
      "start": 47.86,
      "end": 54.82,
      "text": "In crafting, value lives in the object. You protect the object, losing the chair is losing everything."
    },
    {
      "start": 54.82,
      "end": 61.2,
      "text": "In molding, value lives in the specification, the mold, the plastic part,"
    },
    {
      "start": 61.52,
      "end": 63.78,
      "text": "disposable, regenerate it at will."
    },
    {
      "start": 65.54,
      "end": 71.0,
      "text": "And it's not just plastics. The chip industry hit this exact wall."
    },
    {
      "start": 72.58,
      "end": 76.54,
      "text": "In the 1980s, chip designers drew every gate by hand."
    },
    {
      "start": 76.88,
      "end": 81.64,
      "text": "When transistor counts hit tens of thousands, they couldn't keep up."
    },
    {
      "start": 81.64,
      "end": 88.54,
      "text": "So in 1985, they moved up from schematics to verilog, a hardware description language."
    },
    {
      "start": 88.92,
      "end": 93.7,
      "text": "You described what you wanted the chip to do, and a synthesis tool generated the gates."
    },
    {
      "start": 95.24,
      "end": 98.76,
      "text": "But here's the thing, synthesis was non-deterministic."
    },
    {
      "start": 99.38,
      "end": 105.02,
      "text": "Run it twice, get different gates, different wiring, different layout,"
    },
    {
      "start": 105.74,
      "end": 108.52,
      "text": "the output varied every single time."
    },
    {
      "start": 109.62,
      "end": 113.94,
      "text": "What synopsis did was wrap a verification tool chain around the generator."
    },
    {
      "start": 114.66,
      "end": 121.4,
      "text": "Formal equivalence checking using SAT and SMT solvers to produce mathematical proof"
    },
    {
      "start": 121.4,
      "end": 125.66,
      "text": "that the output, whatever it looked like, behaved identically to the spec."
    },
    {
      "start": 126.4,
      "end": 131.12,
      "text": "The gates were different every time. The function was the same every time."
    },
    {
      "start": 132.68,
      "end": 139.62,
      "text": "By 1990, most designs were still schematic based. By the mid 1990s, half had switched."
    },
    {
      "start": 140.28,
      "end": 146.52,
      "text": "Today, all but the most trivial chips use HDL. Every time component counts exceeded"
    },
    {
      "start": 146.52,
      "end": 150.58,
      "text": "what the current abstraction could handle, the industry moved up a level."
    },
    {
      "start": 151.02,
      "end": 155.2,
      "text": "The designer stopped specifying how and started specifying what."
    },
    {
      "start": 155.2,
      "end": 160.62,
      "text": "But this is that same transition for software."
    },
    {
      "start": 161.74,
      "end": 168.68,
      "text": "The prompt is your mold, the code is just plastic, and just like chip synthesis,"
    },
    {
      "start": 169.74,
      "end": 176.98,
      "text": "the code is different every generation. But the tests lock the behavior, the process is deterministic."
    }
  ]
}